
root directory (/ - root)  --> Starting point for the file system, all file structure is under / (Root directory)
/home directory(~ - home)  --> contains all users under it separate

pwd --> print working directory --> where am I? --> displays where you are right now as path
id --> display information about the currently logged-in user

ls /
ls ~
ls /bin
ls -lhS --> display human readable sorting by size
ls -la ~ --> listing all files and directories including hidden ones on user's home directory
ls -ld /etc  --> -d option displays information about the directory, not about its contents
ls -h /etc  --> -h option displays the size in human readable format
ls -Sh /var/log --> -S option displays sorting by size
du -sh ~ --> Note: ls does not display the size of a directory and all its contents. Use du instead
ls -lX /etc --> -X option displays sorting by extension
ls --hide=*.log /var/log --> --hide option hides some files, in this case any files has log extension
ls -lR ~ --> -R options displays directories recursively
ls -li /etc --> -i option displays the inode number
ls -lt --> - t option displays the output sorted by modification time, newest files first
ls -ltu --> -u option displays and sorts by atime
ls -ltu --reverse or ls /ltru --> -r option reversing the sorting order
ls -ltra --> reverse order by modification time with hidden files
ls -l --sort=time
ls -l --sort=size

## Changing directories with cd
cd Desktop/ --> go to Desktop directory
cd .. --> back up one level
cd / --> go to root directory
cd ~ --> go to current user's home directory

Important Directoris: 
/
/home
/bin 
/usr/bin 
/etc
/var
/dev
/media
/boot
/root
